My girlfriend is in a very similar situation.  She has a very bad case of endometriosis.  I've seen the pictures they took, it looks like a spider went crazy inside her.  Her ovaries are literally stuck and appear as if spiderwebbed to the side walls of the uterus (I think it's the uterus but I may be wrong) and one tube is totally blocked while the other allows but a mere trickle.<br>
<br>
Last summer they gave her lupron injections, for 6 months she endured forced menopause.  Between my pain and her mood swings it was not a fun time but we managed. lol<br>
<br>
Sadly the pain is coming back and for her the only real option is a full hysterectomy.  She's 36 and will never bear a child.  I know from doing all I can to comfort her exactly what you are going through Wrin.<br>
<br>
I'm truly sorry.<br>
<br>
I disagree with you on one small but vital point.  It is true that some children are more understanding and tolerant of differences but by and large kids are simply cruel to one another over things like that.  In the case of this poor child I have no doubt they would be the butt end of every joke.<br>
<br>
My daughter for example, she was born with tight heel cords and is a toe walker, horrible for balance and posture and of course it looks odd seeing someone always on their tip toes.  Her doctor fitted her with a  special brace that forced her to walk flat footed, after less than 3 weeks she was begging not to have to wear it because the other kids were picking on her about it.  <br>
<br>
I'm with Idadar on this one.  If the child had any real hope of a pain free and care free life I'd change my mind in a moment.  I don't think that's a possibility and I can tell you bluntly and honestly from my own expierence with chronic pain...<br>
<br>
were it not for my daughter and my girlfriend I'd have ended my life.  That's how bad I hurt and how miserable I am. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mausoleumthenecro>Mausoleum the Necro</A> at: 8/8/03 10:18 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wrinsylkenhand>Wrin Sylkenhand </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle> the fury</span><br>  Posts: 1045<br> <font color=#330000>(8/8/03 10:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=933.topic&index=28>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: To let live or to euthanize? (kinda NSFW, no porn)</span><hr size=1> Thanks Maus. Yeah I too have endometriosis.  Mine is starting to grow on my backmuscles now too.  I would suggest that she talk to her doc about getting Depo-provera shots.  They have made a world of difference for me.<br>
