<br>
I am an overweight man, obese if you will.  Always have been.  Many people hate the obese (some form these boards if I remember corrently) and yet others just like to torture people's emotions.  So I underwent a lot of ridicule as well.  <br>
<br>
Funny thing is, while she has gone through much more teasing than I have, she nearly never lets it bother her.  I have seen her go through being teased in front of large groups to the point that would leave many people in tears, and she just tells them to &quot;buzz off&quot; and goes back to what she's doing.  It's actually quite amazing.  I envy her, she has taught me a lot.  Wrote an essay about it for college a few years back.  Sometimes a disadvantage makes the strongest of people, and those are the people that can teach us a lot.  <br>
<br>
If someone asked me if I'd want the mother of my future children to go through with a pregnancy if we knew beforehand that the child would have downs or some other disease, a relfex would say no.  But then I think of all the things my sister has taught me and given me to strive to be a better man, and I stall.  I think of how happy she always makes herself even when all the circumstances state that she shouldn't, and I change my mind.  If it's a lifetime of physical pain, I'd react to say abort.  But what greatness may be stifled in the process?  I'm not religious or a believer of fate, but sometimes leaving things in the hands of chance might be best. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.aol.com/poeticsarcasm/images/eodsig.jpg" style="border:0;height:200;width:500;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
